e between the Melanesian literature, which informs much of the recent work in the Anthropology of Christianity, and the concepts and theories deriving from Amazonian ethnology, in particular the notions of openness to the other, unstable dualism, and perspectivism, the author provides a fine-grained analysis of the equivocations and paradoxes that underlie the translation processes performed by the different agents involved and their implications for the transformation of the native notion of personhood.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristianityzAmazon River Region. 0aConversionxChristianity. 0aIndigenous peopleszAmazon River RegionxHistory. 0aMissions, BrazilianzAmazon River RegionxHistory. 0aPakaasnovos IndiansxReligion. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamazonian ethnology.  aanthropology of evangelical christianity.  aanthropology of missionary work.  abrazilian amazon.  abrazilian indigengous.  achristian amazon.  achristian amazonians.  achristian missionary work in the amazon.  aconversion of amazonian indigenous peoples.  aevangelical missionaries to south america.  aindigenous amazonians.  amelanesian literature.  amissionaries to south america.  amissionary work.  anative amazonians.  anew tribes mission.  asouth american evangelicals.  awari.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052028913040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096384940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963849423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963849/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY